<Document>
<name>Icefields Parkway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Icefields Parkway</h2><p><i>Alberta, Canada · Highway 93, Lake Louise to Jasper</i></p><p><b>Frequently called the most scenic drive in North America: 232 km between glaciers.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>215 km (133 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4 hrs no stops; full day with</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>June–September</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Wildlife on road (grizzly, moose, sheep), weather changes fast at altitude, gas only at Saskatchewan Crossing in summer</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>310</td></tr></table><hr><p>144 miles of glacier-flanked corridor connecting Banff and Jasper National Parks. The road reaches 2,069 m at Bow Summit. Every 10 minutes there is another viewpoint that would be the headline of any other drive. Look for grizzlies (we saw three on one June afternoon), mountain goats on cliffs, bighorn sheep on the road, woodland caribou (rare), gray wolf (rarer). The Columbia Icefield in the middle of the route is the largest icefield in the Canadian Rockies — 325 km², feeding glaciers to three oceans. Drive it slowly. Park reservations required in summer; book ahead.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Lake Louise</b> — Postcard glacial lake at 1,750 m. Chateau Lake Louise hotel on the shore. Walk the Lakeshore Trail (4 km round-trip) for the best photos.</li><li><b>Bow Lake &amp; Num-ti-jah Lodge</b> — Iconic red-roofed 1937 lodge against turquoise Bow Lake. The lodge's founder, Jimmy Simpson, guided here for 50 years.</li><li><b>Peyto Lake from Bow Summit</b> — Arrowhead-shaped electric-blue lake — short paved walk to the overlook. Color is from suspended glacial flour.</li><li><b>Mistaya Canyon</b> — Limestone slot carved by the Mistaya River, swirled and water-polished. Short walk from parking.</li><li><b>Columbia Icefield / Athabasca Glacier</b> — Drive-up glacier that you can step onto with a guide. SkyWalk glass platform extends 35 m over a cliff. The glacier has retreated 1.5 km since 1844 — markers show the rate.</li><li><b>Athabasca Falls</b> — Powerful, not tall — the Niagara of the Canadian Rockies. Multiple viewing platforms, water-carved limestone slots.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
